Sure! Here's a basic example of how to split data and build a machine learning model using Python with scikit-learn. This example uses a classification task with the popular Iris dataset.


---

‚úÖ Step 1: Import Libraries

import pandas as pd
from sklearn.datasets import load_iris
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score


---

‚úÖ Step 2: Load Dataset

# Load iris dataset
iris = load_iris()
X = pd.DataFrame(iris.data, columns=iris.feature_names)
y = pd.Series(iris.target)


---

‚úÖ Step 3: Split the Data

# Split data: 70% training, 30% testing
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42
)


---

‚úÖ Step 4: Build and Train the Model

# Initialize the model
model = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)

# Train the model
model.fit(X_train, y_train)


---

‚úÖ Step 5: Predict and Evaluate

# Make predictions
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate accuracy
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.2f}")


---

üîÅ Summary

train_test_split: Used to divide your dataset into training and test parts.

RandomForestClassifier: Just one example model‚Äîyou can swap in SVM, KNN, etc.

accuracy_score: Measures how well your model performs.


